Before we begin answering this problem, we must first define two of the important concepts that we will use. First is the weighted average cost of capital or WACC for short. This is the rate at which the company is expected to pay its investors for the assets. It can be calculated using this formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Weighted average cost of capital}&=\text{Debt} \times\text{Weight of debt}\\
&+\text{Equity} \times \text{Weight of equity}
\end{aligned}$$

The next important concept that we will use is the debt/equity ratio. This is basically the numerical value of how much of the company's value is split between debt and equity. This can simply be done by dividing the weight of the debt by the weight of the equity. 

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Debt-Equity ratio}&=\dfrac{\text{Weight of debt}}{\text{Weight of equity}}
\end{aligned}$$

We also know that the weight of the debt and the weight of equity, when added together is equal. to $1.00$ or $100\%$. This means that if we let $\text{w}$ be the weight of the debt, then we can represent the unknown weights as:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{w}&=\text{Weight of debt}\\
1-\text{w}&=\text{Weight of equity}
\end{aligned}$$
